        <h2>Stack: The dedicated estimating specialist</h2>
        <p>Stack's strength is focus. It does digital takeoff and estimating, and it does them very well. The takeoff tools are fast and well-designed for professional estimators who process multiple bids per week. The estimating database handles complex assemblies across multiple trades, and the cloud-based platform enables multiple estimators to collaborate on concurrent bids.</p>

        <p>Stack is used by GCs and specialty contractors across residential and commercial work — it's more trade-agnostic than Buildxact. An electrical contractor, a mechanical contractor, and a commercial GC can all use Stack effectively for their takeoff work.</p>

        <p>The gap: Stack stops at estimating. After the bid is won, you need separate software for project management, scheduling, client communication, and job costing. For companies that already have a PM platform and just need better takeoff, this is fine. For small builders who don't want to manage multiple subscriptions, it's a limitation.</p>

        <h2>Buildxact: The integrated small-builder solution</h2>
        <p>Buildxact's value proposition is different: it's not trying to be the best estimating tool — it's trying to be a complete enough platform for small residential builders that they don't need anything else. Takeoff, estimating, proposals, basic scheduling, client portal, job costing, and QuickBooks integration — all in one subscription at a lower price than Buildertrend.</p>

        <p>For a custom homebuilder doing 3–8 projects per year who currently estimates in Excel and schedules in a notebook, Buildxact is a significant upgrade that doesn't require managing multiple software subscriptions. The integration between estimating and PM means your estimate becomes your job budget without re-entry.</p>

        <p>The trade-off: Buildxact's individual features are shallower than dedicated tools. The takeoff is good, not great. The PM features are basic. For a builder who scales up and needs more depth, Buildxact will eventually feel constraining.</p>

