        <p>When you factor in the cost of a separate PM tool for Stack users, Buildxact becomes more cost-competitive for small builders who need both estimating and basic PM.</p>

        <h2>Who should choose Stack</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Dedicated estimating departments at GC or specialty contractor companies</li>
          <li>Commercial GCs who already have Procore or similar for PM</li>
          <li>Companies that estimate across multiple trades or project types</li>
          <li>Professional estimators who process many bids and need the fastest, most accurate takeoff tool</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Who should choose Buildxact</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Small residential builders who want estimating + PM in one affordable platform</li>
          <li>Custom homebuilders doing fewer than 15 projects per year</li>
          <li>Contractors currently using Excel who want to upgrade to integrated software</li>
          <li>Builders who find Buildertrend's price prohibitive and want a cost-effective alternative</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

        <h3>Does Stack include project management?</h3>
        <p>No. Stack is an estimating and takeoff platform. Once a bid is won, you need a separate tool for project management. It integrates with some PM platforms but doesn't include PM functionality itself.</p>

        <h3>Is Buildxact's takeoff as good as Stack's?</h3>
        <p>Stack's takeoff has more depth and speed for professional estimating operations. Buildxact's takeoff is competent for residential work but isn't optimized for estimators running high-volume bid operations. The difference matters more as your estimating volume increases.</p>

        <h3>What about Buildertrend as an alternative to both?</h3>
        <p>Buildertrend (Complete plan, $1,099/mo) includes estimating and takeoff tools along with a much more comprehensive PM platform. If you're a residential builder growing toward $2M+ in annual revenue, Buildertrend is worth evaluating even though it's more expensive — the depth in client management, financials, and scheduling justifies the cost for the right business.</p>

